<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910416-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>910416-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- NEC Corp.:   Company Begins Marketing   `Fault-Tolerant' Computer</HL><DATE>04/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   NIPNY SRA</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)INDUSTRIAL TECHNOLOGY andamp; PRODUCTION, QUALITY CONTROL (ITC)</IN><RE>JAPAN (JA)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)</RE><LP>   NEC Corp. said it has begun marketing a &quot;fault-tolerant&quot;computer system designed to continue functioning even in theevent of a failure in some of its parts or software.   NEC said it expects sales of the model, called NEC SuperTolerant FT20, to amount to 600 units in the first threeyears.</LP><TEXT>   The computer system is aimed at the telecommunicationsmarket, and firms using on-line transaction processing(OLTP), NEC said.   The computer systems are produced by Stratus Computer Inc.of the U.S., which is based in Marlboro, Mass., an NECspokesman said. Under an agreement allowing the Japanese firmto market Stratus's computers under its own name, the unitswill be shipped to Japan where NEC will add its own hardwareand software to the systems, the spokesman said.   The fault-tolerant computer systems will be marketed at 78million yen ($513,384) each.</TEXT></DOC>